{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539363"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:40:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:40:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16590"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16590"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.11,0.03,0.17,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9281"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9281"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16590"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93060"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4972"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"7937"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41894"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a persistent knee lesion present for eight months. She migrated from India one year ago, where she was previously a cleaner at the general hospital in her local district. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. The lesion began as a small, reddish-brown papule on her left knee that has gradually enlarged. It is not painful or pruritic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a well-demarcated, reddish-brown plaque with a wart-like appearance on her left knee. There is no ulceration or surrounding cellulitis. The rest of her skin examination is normal. Her chest examination is clear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discoid lupus erythematosus","Lupus vulgaris","Sarcoidosis","Keloid scar","Tuberculosis verrucosa cutis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of cutaneous tuberculosis, specifically \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberculosis verrucosa cutis\u003C/strong\u003E. The key diagnostic features include the chronic progression, reddish-brown plaque which is painless, and working in a hospital in an endemic country. Whilst cutaneous tuberculosis is rare and can present with many forms, tuberculosis verrucosa cutis as demonstrated in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELupus vulgaris\u003C/strong\u003E is the second most common form of cutaneous tuberculosis, representing a chronic, progressive form of the disease with characteristic apple-jelly nodules which are not present in this case. It also commences as reddish-brown plaques but the gelatinous appearance is absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscoid lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with erythematous plaques with adherent scaling and follicular plugging, leading to scarring and atrophy. It tends to be photosensitive and the appearance is different to this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with reddish-brown papules and plaques, but these typically appear as multiple lesions and may show a yellowish-brown translucent appearance on diascopy. Other systemic manifestations are often present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeloid scar\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a firm, raised, shiny and smooth growth extending beyond the original injury site. It requires previous trauma and would not be enlarging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConfirmation of cutaneous tuberculosis requires histopathological examination showing tuberculoid granulomas, and microbiological studies including PCR and culture for \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E. Treatment involves standard anti-tuberculous therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cutaneous tuberculosis should be suspected in chronic, non-healing skin lesions, especially in patients from TB-endemic areas."],"references":["Ngan V, Oakley A. Cutaneous tuberculosis. DermNet NZ. 2023. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/cutaneous-tuberculosis","Ho CK, Ho MH, Chong LY. Cutaneous tuberculosis in Hong Kong: an update. Hong Kong Med J. 2006.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16912353/","Santos JB, Figueiredo AR, Ferraz CE, Oliveira MH, Silva PG, Medeiros VL. Cutaneous tuberculosis: epidemiologic, etiopathogenic and clinical aspects - part I. Anais Brasileiros de Dermatolgia. 2014.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4008050/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93060"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16590"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93060"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-05T16:25:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-05T16:27:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9281"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"t